metadata.name: {Lumina} #354
metadata.description:
The restitution of a breath
Your breath is your artwork

{Lumina} is part of the installation Σ Lumina taking place at Musée d’Orsay. A free live minting is scheduled from February 13th to March 10th, 2024. 

Breath, the vital essence, embodies our interconnection. It carries our shared heritage. A medium that helps Σ Lumina to unite the physical and the digital, the living with the coded. The voices of Orsay resonate within us, their breath becoming ours, landscaping our common creation.


Art curators of {Le Code d’Orsay}:
Christophe Leribault,
Président de l’Établissement public du musée d’Orsay et du musée de l’Orangerie
Virginie Donzeaud, Administratrice générale adjointe

16x16
HTML, js, Webgl
Location: Musée d’Orsay

metadata.name: Stippled Sketch #183
metadata.description:
Stippled Sketch is an experimental attempt to imitate the result of sitting down and mindlessly finding form on the page. The process of pressing the pen to paper in a rhythmic, repeated pattern can be a form of meditation, much like doodling. 

The form at the center of the sketch can sometimes take a clear and recognizable shape, but it can also appear meandering and meaningless at times. Some forms appear more often than others (such as a clover and circle), but the equation at the core of the algorithm has surprised me quite a few times with unique and unusual shapes, even after reviewing thousands of previews. 

I like to think of this collection as a reflection of a time in my life when I wanted to say so much—and I could put the pen to the paper, but I knew that no words would have any effect, so I sketched to focus my attention on something else instead. 

— — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — — 
Special thanks to Laurent Houdard and Lisa Orth for helping with a few technical aspects.

metadata.name: Glossolalia #120
metadata.description:
This series is ultimately about catharsis. The compositions can be chaotic and maybe even a little messy, but they also can be vibrant and diverse… which is really what this is trying to celebrate: diversity and expression.

Simply, it’s about the emotions associated with whatever frees you.

Please see the linked fxtext article (on the main project page) for a more in-depth dissection of the concept. It’s less of a technical discussion, and more about the experience of the artist, and how it became linked with the feelings they associate with the art.

In live mode:

For higher resolutions, you can append “&density=2” to the url to double the size, “&density=3” to triple, and so on.
(This is highly recommended.)

To adjust grain, you can append “&grain=##” to the url. 40 is the default, and 0 will remove it completely.

metadata.name: angels #191
metadata.description:
manifestations of divine madness, twisted and weathered, sketched from memory

made in clojurescript+webgl

press "s" to save a png
press "r" to re-render at the current window size
manually set the resolution by adding "?resolution={width}x{height}" to the URL

metadata.name: Remains #189
metadata.description:
This series explores the remnants and imprints of past events; the unintended consequences and marks left behind: The floor of a painter's studio, layered with splatters and spills; the face of a rock, sculpted by the relentless touch of water and ice; the rusty hood of a forsaken car, weathered and chipped under the harsh sun.

The art piece is crafted by an algorithm simulating the effects of abrasion from a consistent yet dynamic process. It links a thousand pairs of points, harmoniously shifting across the canvas, with delicate lines. At each intersection of these lines, color is applied. To produce the final piece, multiple layers of varying colors and intensities are superimposed.

------

Controls:

- [x] Save a PNG

- [1] Set height to 768
- [2] Set height to 1152 
- [3] Set height to 1536 (default)
- [4] Set height to 2304
- [5] Set height to 3072* 
- [6] Set height to 6144*
- [7] Set height to 9216*
- [8] Set height to 11520*

URL parameters:

- &height={HEIGHT} explicitly sets the render height


* images with height over 3000 pixels render without animating, downloads a PNG automatically after rendering

Please note that high resolution outputs will take several minutes or even longer to render. Highest resolutions have only been successfully tested with Safari on a Mac. If you would like to have assistance in creating high resolution outputs, please contact the author.

metadata.name: RushGushBlush #350
metadata.description:
Let's celebrate #fxhashturnsone with a cascade of colors!

This is just my second release on fxhash and I couldn't be happier to dedicate this project, however simple, to this amazing community.

I could go on describing the details of this piece but honestly I just wanted to create something very colorful for the party, without putting too many hidden meanings! :)
(Or maybe not...)

Happy birthday fxhash!

---

80% of primary sales will be donated to the Processing Foundation and Save Pakistan.

---

There are 17 different palettes and 3 formats, hope you'll find a combination that makes you happy!
The texture might look weird in thumbnails, so I recommend opening the piece in full screen and/or download the png by pressing "s".
